- Excuse me.
- Now what?

326
00:20:45,360 --> 00:20:46,884
I'm sorry. Son.

327
00:20:46,961 --> 00:20:48,588
Alex. You have
to take this now?

328
00:20:48,663 --> 00:20:49,925
This may be an emergency.

329
00:20:49,998 --> 00:20:51,829
Hey. My grandson
is reading the four questions!

330
00:20:51,899 --> 00:20:53,992
- Eli. Please. I'm sorry.
- No. It's OK.

331
00:20:54,068 --> 00:20:57,560
No. No. No.
Go ahead. Start again.

332
00:20:57,639 --> 00:21:00,403
Ignores his duties
at the firm for years.

333
00:21:00,475 --> 00:21:03,239
- Now he has to work.
- Mitchell. Not now.

334
00:21:03,311 --> 00:21:04,869
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

335
00:21:04,946 --> 00:21:07,039
- What did you say?
- You heard me.

336
00:21:07,115 --> 00:21:10,573
You're talkin' to me about duty?
Dad. I know all about duty.

337
00:21:10,652 --> 00:21:13,143
Duty to my family
as well as my work.

338
00:21:13,221 --> 00:21:16,156
- What about me?
- Alex. Don't start this.

339
00:21:16,224 --> 00:21:20,058
I mean. Where were you. Huh?
I mean. Where were you?

340
00:21:20,128 --> 00:21:22,096
At least I've made an effort
to be here.

341
00:21:22,163 --> 00:21:27,260
Eli. Read it like you mean it.

342
00:21:27,335 --> 00:21:30,429
- "Why is this night..."
- Hey. Everybody.

343
00:21:30,505 --> 00:21:34,771
Well. At least you got here
before Elijah did.

344
00:21:34,842 --> 00:21:37,970
- Uncle Stephen. Pappy. Mom.
- Hello. Darling.

345
00:21:38,046 --> 00:21:39,377
Hey. Little man.

346
00:21:39,447 --> 00:21:41,472
- Good to see you. Son.
- Good to see you. Too. Dad.

347
00:21:41,549 --> 00:21:43,710
- Glad you could make it.
- Yeah. Me. Too.

348
00:21:48,923 --> 00:21:51,357
You want to find out if anybody
else would like the last piece?

349
00:21:52,927 --> 00:21:55,088
Would anybody else like
this last piece of brisket?

350
00:21:55,163 --> 00:21:56,255
No. Thanks.

351
00:21:56,331 --> 00:21:57,491
At least somebody else here
likes the wine.

352
00:21:59,033 --> 00:22:00,523
You're not doing too bad
yourself.

353
00:22:00,601 --> 00:22:03,934
Mom. Mean brisket.

354
00:22:04,005 --> 00:22:05,097
It's my best work yet.
Isn't it?

355
00:22:05,173 --> 00:22:06,299
It's wonderful.

356
00:22:09,944 --> 00:22:13,778
What is it?
Tell me. Stephen. Tell me.

357
00:22:13,848 --> 00:22:14,940
- Is he all right?
- He's all right.

358
00:22:15,016 --> 00:22:17,678
He's having a good time.

359
00:22:17,752 --> 00:22:18,844
Abby Staley came back today.

360
00:22:18,920 --> 00:22:20,581
- Who?
- What. Honey?

361
00:22:20,655 --> 00:22:22,850
Abby Staley...
she came back to class today.

362
00:22:22,924 --> 00:22:24,516
- Who's she?
- She did?

363
00:22:24,592 --> 00:22:26,150
- Who did?
- This little girl in his class.

364
00:22:26,227 --> 00:22:28,821
She ran away with an older boy.
She's twelve years old.

365
00:22:28,896 --> 00:22:31,797
This happens
at artsy-fartsy school?

366
00:22:31,866 --> 00:22:34,767
- Kids run away?
- Did you talk to her?

367
00:22:34,836 --> 00:22:37,430
No. I don't even like her.

368
00:22:37,505 --> 00:22:39,598
She thinks she's cooler than
everybody else in the class.

369
00:22:39,674 --> 00:22:41,301
If she wants to run away.
It's OK with me.

370
00:22:41,376 --> 00:22:43,037
You should be a little more
compassionate than that.

371
00:22:43,111 --> 00:22:45,477
She's obviously going through
a very hard time right now.

372
00:22:45,546 --> 00:22:47,207
Whatever.

373
00:22:47,281 --> 00:22:49,340
Do you ever think about
running away?

374
00:22:49,417 --> 00:22:50,714
Sometimes.

375
00:22:50,785 --> 00:22:55,051
I would run away. Too.
From such a farkakte school.

376
00:22:55,123 --> 00:22:58,320
- That's helpful. Mitchell.
- Come on. Dad. That's enough.

377
00:22:58,393 --> 00:23:00,258
Enough!

378
00:23:00,328 --> 00:23:01,556
He said it.

379
00:23:01,629 --> 00:23:04,530
Good for you.

380
00:23:06,567 --> 00:23:07,693
You want to tell us
why you didn't pick up...

381
00:23:07,769 --> 00:23:09,031
your grandmother
from dialysis today?

382
00:23:09,103 --> 00:23:11,094
Alex. You promised me
you wouldn't say anything.

383
00:23:11,172 --> 00:23:13,834
- It's no big deal.
- I think it's a big deal.

384
00:23:13,908 --> 00:23:16,433
Asher. We ask so little of you.
We counted on you...

385
00:23:16,511 --> 00:23:17,603
Do you know how serious it is?

386
00:23:17,678 --> 00:23:19,669
Do you have any idea
what dialysis is?

387
00:23:19,747 --> 00:23:21,180
Yeah. Dad.
I do. As a matter of fact.

388
00:23:21,249 --> 00:23:23,979
Kidney dialysis
is the process...

389
00:23:24,051 --> 00:23:27,714
of filtering the accumulated
waste products of metabolism...

390
00:23:27,789 --> 00:23:28,881
from the blood of a patient...

391
00:23:28,956 --> 00:23:30,423
whose kidneys
aren't functioning properly.

392
00:23:30,491 --> 00:23:31,753
You guys hear that?

393
00:23:31,826 --> 00:23:33,760
If this is too much
responsibility for you...

394
00:23:33,828 --> 00:23:35,386
I don't want you
fighting over me.

395
00:23:35,463 --> 00:23:37,021
When I was his age...

396
00:23:37,098 --> 00:23:39,123
I supported a wife. A kid...

397
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:40,633
Oh. That's not true. Dad!

398
00:23:40,701 --> 00:23:43,192
When you were his age.
I wasn't even born yet.

399
00:23:43,271 --> 00:23:46,468
All of you. Let it pass!
Let it be!

400
00:23:46,541 --> 00:23:49,169
As a matter of fact. I had
a very interesting experience...

401
00:23:49,243 --> 00:23:50,505
aFTer I leFT dialysis.

402
00:23:50,578 --> 00:23:54,139
- What happened?
- I got in the cab...

403
00:23:56,017 --> 00:23:59,145
and then I went
to my mother's old building.

404
00:23:59,220 --> 00:24:01,950
- Why did you do that?
- Didn't you go home?

405
00:24:02,023 --> 00:24:04,992
I'm not sure. I just...

406
00:24:05,059 --> 00:24:08,324
I just found myself there.

407
00:24:09,964 --> 00:24:11,488
I think it's a sign.

408
00:24:11,566 --> 00:24:14,865
Honey. What the hell
are you talking about?

409
00:24:14,936 --> 00:24:17,097
A sign? What sign?

410
00:24:17,171 --> 00:24:20,304
- Look. Granny. I'm sorry.
- Oh. That's all right. Honey.

411
00:24:21,676 --> 00:24:23,143
I'm gonna go drain my dragon.

412
00:24:25,480 --> 00:24:29,211
- Drain his what?
- His dragon. Dear.

413
00:24:29,283 --> 00:24:32,081
You can't always run away
from consequences. Asher.

414
00:24:32,153 --> 00:24:33,677
Sooner or later.
You're going to have to...

415
00:24:35,690 --> 00:24:37,783
Oh. Jesus.

416
00:24:37,859 --> 00:24:39,349
Silent. But violent.

417
00:24:44,799 --> 00:24:48,200
